<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Try reading what I post instead of just ranting.  Nowhere in my post did I state that he was in the right and you were in the wrong.  I simply offered another point of view, that of a bard.  As well as asking a few questions, none of which I noticed you answered.<P>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by Blurem:<BR><STRONG>Ok, next time I'll just buff and melee, we know that Enchanters are a melee hybrid.<BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>The issue here is communication, neither of you bothered except of course to tell him not to charm.  Perhaps you should have.<P>    <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>First up, I was in the group first, he joined later.  <BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Fine, but the question I asked was if it had been reversed would you have talked to him about your role in the group or would you have simply took over CC and assumed he would shift his efforts elsewhere?<P>Would you have been content to sit back and buff if you joined a group with a bard doing CC?<P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>Second, his "charm" message was a one line "i've charmed %T" that he threw out in the middle of the fight.<BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>And your charm message is not a 1 liner thrown out in the middle of a fight?  It is not like he has a lot of options.  You could have asked him to bold the message in some manner ... be glad he gave you a message, most enchanters in my raiding parties do not bother with even that.<P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>He knew I was doing crowd control.<BR>Durring the fight my job is CC.  Durring the fight, if there's no Chanter his job is CC.  <BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>A common take on the matter, perhaps he feels differently.  Funny thing, in my time spent playing this game I have seen some pretty amazing pullers that were not monks/shadowknights.  I have seen paladins and shaman do CC almost as well as an enchanter could.<P>There is a reason groups shout looking for a bard or an enchanter.  The reason they do this is because we are interchangable.  We can both do CC and we can both do it efficiently.  We both supply mana and haste.  In the end there is not a heck of a lot of difference between what a bard can bring to the party and what an enchanter can      <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>As for CC, you are right he knew you were doing CC so he did not mezz.  Charm is a whole different ballgame, charm is an amazing method of dealing massive amounts of damage utilizing a mob against another mob.  It has a SECONDARY effect of being a form of CC.<P>So he left the CC to you and he used charm to leverage greater damage in combat.<P>The fact of the matter is you had a routine and you were not willing to give an inch to anyone who might "infinge" upon your domain.  You assumed he would join and instantly be subservient, you state that if another enchanter had joined you would have talked to them about their role in the group yet you did not bother to discuss with the bard what his role would be.<P>Personally I can handle someone charming, it is annoying and it takes a little bit to get used to but I can deal with it.<P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>Durring the fight With a chanter he has alot more useful spells, his haste, his shield spells, healing, damageshields.  <BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Just like any other spells this is group dependent.  A good bard can twist 3 songs, if he is charming that still leaves him 2 more songs to do other "useful" things.<P>Can I state with certainty that your group would have been better off without him charming?  No, I cannot.  Just as I could not state the opposite.<P>Charm is a very powerful tool when used correctly.<P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> <BR><STRONG><BR>When he starts mezzing/charming durring combat he relegates me to sitting int he corner and buffing.  When his song breaks, I have no way of knowing what happened, what he's going to do about it and what he expects of me.  Should I try to remez the 2 additional creatures trying to eat him?  Am I going to mez the one he's trying to recharm?  Do I just sit and cast chain rune on him while he plays chanter?<BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>That is called communication and compromise, it what grouping is all about.  If you wish to know what he would like you do do in this case, asking him would likely work.<P>Do you think it is any different with an enchanter?  When your charm breaks or your mezz breaks and mobs come pound the heck out of you how does everyone else know what to do?  You are just not used to being in that situation      <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Do you ask the paladin/cleric to stun your mobs.  Do you ask other casters to root your mobs?  How do you expect them to know what to do to help you out?  Yet somehow the good players always manage it don't they?<P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>When I group with another chanter (rare in exp, common on raids) we work out a system.  The lowest chanter with C2 does C2, next highest does Brilliance/enlighten, next does GoB.  If no epic, one does AQ/WR. <P>When mobs inc we break down who's gonna do "what" primarily.  In hate for instance, if a cleric, a rat and a Rev inc, I know I'm Rev First, another might be Cleric first and so on.  Once I lock down my target I look to see what's not locked and how's having problems.<BR></STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>So you are willing to communicate with other enchanters and work with them.  But if it is a bard you shut him down?  How about the next time you group with a bard you pretend he is an enchanter ... perhaps then you will manage to communicate with him and sort out your roles in a group.  <P>     <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><STRONG><BR>I do not just break out the GFlux and have at it because it's an awsome tool and I can.  Any bets on how fast I'd be TL'd out?</STRONG><BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Another interesting comment that has no bearing whatsoever on the arguement.  I see no reference to the bard breaking out AOE and breaking your mezzes.  All I see is him charming to improve the kill rate of the group, letting everyone know he was charming by way of an emote and of course you, the enchanter, unable to deal with the complexities of someone charming in your group.<P>The funny thing about enchanters is the vast majority of them are not used to working with other people.  Other people are forced to work with us, we go of the deep end if they do not and yet most enchanters are not capable of reciprocating.  I cannot believe the number of posts about enchanters hating to group with other enchanters or enchanters hating to group with bards.  <P>Take a lesson from bards, they actually manage to group with each other in a complimentary fashion  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>To many member of my class have the "It is my way or the highway" mentality.  No wonder bards hate grouping with enchanters      <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Thankful some of us are willing to actually talk to other group members.  <P>I still remember the first time a bard asked me if he could charm and I said yes, I just asked him to make sure he let me know he was charming and if he was in trouble and needed a hand.  <P>His response: "Wow, I have never had an enchanter say yes before"<P>I thought that was rather odd given how powerful charm was.  So I kept my eye on him and when he started taking damage I would drop a quick stun on the mob letting him get his charm off.<P>Did it add to my work?  Yes, but hey I like a challenge.<P>More importantly though, did it make him happy and feel more useful?  Yes it did.<P>So I say again, do not be afraid of new ideas.  Give other people a chance.  Communication and compromise is the key.  You would be amazed at what some players are capable of accomplishing, I know I am.  Of course if you never give them the chance, you will never see what I am talking about.<P>Regards,<P>--------------------<P>Zanithar TideBreaker<BR>Phantasmist <BR>Cazic Thule<BR>250 JewelCraft
