<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I'm going to poke my nose in here and just say a few words from a bard's point of view. (Which Zanithar has done quite well, in my opinion - I think due to a very similar discussion on the bard boards a while back.  Kudos to Zanithar for (hopefully) learning a little about bards and our capabilities during that time)<P>I very rarely group with enchanters.  Not through personal choice, but simply because, of the people I regularly play with, none of them play an enchanter.<P>Hence, for my groups I am the primary crowd control.  I am the "enchanter".  This has always been the case, and until a few new enchanter friends attain higher levels, will continue to be the case.<P>I can perform crowd control as well as any enchanter on a pull of 7 mobs or less.  I will admit right now, that a <I>good</I> enchanter will perform crowd control better than me, simply because of the fact that you recast mez fewer times. (mine lasts up to 18 seconds before I have to re-mez)<P>Bards typically twist 3 songs.  Some (due to a top notch computer and connection) can regularly twist 4.  I typically twist 3 songs, but can twist 4 if required (it's too hard to maintain continually, but I can do it for short 'bursts').  A bard's charm has a slightly longer duration than the rest of our songs.  Because of this, I can charm a mob, keep a full 3 song twist going, and time my recharm so that it hits the mob so fast after breaking, it has no chance to swing at me.  If used in this way, bard charm is very powerful.  Not only do I keep my regular 3 song twist up, but I add the melee damage of a mob to the group's output on the main target.  Anyway, you guys are enchanters, I don't need to tell you the pros/cons of charm.<P>If I am the "enchanter" of the group, and an enchanter joins (due to my regular grouping friends, it doesn't happen often, but it's happened enough) I immediately establish how we are going to work <I>together</I>.  Bards and enchanters can really step on each other's toes.  We can be undefeatable working together, or total mayhem working against each other.  Communication is key.<P>Unless you're pulling huge trains and lining them up for single-slaughter, either can do good crowd control.  This often leaves whoever isn't doing crowd control 'out in the cold' so to speak.  Especially if it's the enchanter, because it's your primary role in the vast majority of groups.  This is how I feel, because in the overwhelming majority of my groups, I am the 'enchanter'.  That being said, bards do have more viable alternatives than enchanters, if crowd control, haste and slow is already covered.  Any bard who does not believe this, does not know their class to it's full potential.  For this reason, I will usually use these alternatives, and the enchanter will handle crowd control.<P>But, if there's only one extra mob, I'd much rather charm it than mez it.  Why allow it to stand idly, when I could be adding it's melee output to the fray, with minimal risk?  This is why I will state that I will charm an extra mob on multiple pulls.  I have a hotkey for announcing my charm, and use it <I>before</I> I actually charm, so everyone knows to leave it alone, unless I ask for help.<P>I can understand why enchanters would feel uncomfortable with a situation like this.  Crowd control is 'your' job.  It's what you learned to do, by force of habit, and it's a damn hard habit to break.  I know, because I learned to play with the same mentality.  But sometimes a break from the norm can be refreshing, and allow you to see the virtues of other classes you might not have known about previously.<P>This is part of what makes a good player.  This is also why good bards and enchanters are often talked about well after they've left.  An adaptable player playing a class with very adaptable abilities is truely a sight to behold.<P>Put two of them together, and you should have a powerful combination.  But often, they end up 'getting in each other's way'.  Why?  Lack of communication.<P>Next time you group with a bard, discuss your strategies.  Maybe the bard is not familiar with crowd control, and does different things with his songs in the first place.  It's quite possible.  Or in my case, I would immediately discuss who does what, so I'm working with the enchanter, rather than against them.<P>Anyone who compares a ranger's healing to a bard's mez is quite unimformed...<P>--------------------<P><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=21087" TARGET=_blank>Andrina Swiftfoot</A> Level 52 Half Elf Minstrel of Xegony's Anklebiter's Brigade<BR>Mukk Donalds Level 29 Ogre Warrior of the Anklebiter's Brigade
</FONT>
