<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Ok, I've played a bard and chanter both 50+, I'm not saying I know everything, but I've got some stuff to say on it and I'll make this post simple.<P>Chanter duties: Hastes/slows, mind buffs, crowd control. Always and forever.<BR>Bard duties: SUPPORT CLASS. Haste/slows when there is nothing better, mana songs (always useful!), crowd control when there is nothing better, melee (not a major damage dealer, but it adds up with decent weapons), support songs (regen/ac/DS/etc... These all stack and help the party tons), and lots more.<P>If you are a bard and have a chanter in the group, and you start charming or mezzing you are wasting YOUR ABILITIES. Why the heck would you take the time to do crowd control when someone else can do it better and you can continue to help the part in other ways? Let the chanter do his job, you do YOURS which is supporting the party as a whole by playing your beneficial group songs.<P>No coordination is needed. Leave the crowd control to the chanter, its their job. If a druid is in a group and a cleric joins, no coordination needed. The cleric is main healer. The druid is backup heals and goes on to other duties. Clerics are healers. Its what they do. Druids are a support class, just like bards. They fill in where needed (dealing damage/heals/buffs/etc).<P>Its not rocket science guys. The role of a support class is fill in where needed and to figure out how to best support the current classes in your group, not to try to do someone else's job.<P>On another note, the thing about keeping 7 mobs occupied. You apparently aren't paying much attention to aggro  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> You said you can keep 2 occupied by charming one and putting it on a second mob. The way aggro works is your pet will NOT keep aggro, if it is within range of a PC, it will start chomping down on that PC, sure your pet will be hitting it, but it will ignore that for any PC on its aggro list within range.
</FONT>
